ew eHarmony Commercial|url=http://loudwire.com/limp-bizkit-fred-durst-eharmony-commercials/?fb44|website=Loudwire.tv|publisher=Loudwire|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n| 2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Fanatic (2019 film)|The Fanatic]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3555972/heres-john-travolta-fred-dursts-stalker-film-fanatic/|title=Here\u2019s John Travolta in Fred Durst\u2019s Stalker Film \u2018The Fanatic\u2019|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=2019-04-16|website=Bloody Disgusting!|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n| 2019\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| [[40th Golden Raspberry Awards|2020]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n| ''[[The Fanatic (2019 film)|The Fanatic]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"Razzies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.razzies.com/razz-newz.html|title=RAZZ NEWZ - The Razzies!|website=razzies.com}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Official}}\n* [http://www.limpbizkit.com/ Limp Bizkit website]\n* {{IMDb name|0004890}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p240084}}\n\n{{Limp Bizkit}}\n{{Fred Durst}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Durst, Fred}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Limp Bizkit members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Jacksonville, Florida]]\n[[Category:Musicians from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Nu metal singers]]\n[[Category:People from Gastonia, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Rap metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Rappers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American tattoo artists]]\n[[Category:Film directors from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Singers from Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Florida]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Florida]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Fred Durst\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = 13-06-09 RiP Limp Bizkit Fred Durst 1.JPG\n| caption          = Durst with Limp Bizkit in 2013\n| birth_name       = William Frederick Durst\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], U.S.\n| origin           = Jacksonville, Florida, U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Nu metal]]\n* [[rap metal]]\n* [[rap rock]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist| \n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* producer\n* actor\n* film director\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| years_active     = 1993\u2013present\n| label            = [[Shrapnel Records|Shrapnel]]\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Limp Bizkit]]\n* [[Method Man]]\n* [[Korn]]\n* [[Kevin Rudolf]]\n* [[Soulfly]]\n* [[Les Claypool]]\n* [[Insane Clown Posse]]\n* [[Raekwon]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[Scott Weiland]]\n* [[Staind]]\n* [[Puddle of Mudd]]\n* [[Eminem]]\n* [[Tommy Lee]]\n* [[Lil Wayne]]\n* [[Primus (band)]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.freddurst.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''William Frederick Durst''' (born August 20, 1970) is an American rapper, singer, songwriter, producer, actor, and film director. He is best known as the frontman of the [[rap rock]] band [[Limp Bizkit]], formed in 1994, with whom he has released six studio albums. \n\nSince 2006, Durst has worked on [[independent films]]. He costarred in ''[[Population 436]]'', and made his directorial debut in 2007, with ''[[The Education of Charlie Banks]]''. He followed with ''[[The Longshots]]'' in 2008. His latest film, ''[[The Fanatic (2019 film)|The Fanatic]]'', came out in 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nDurst was born in [[Jacksonville, Florida]] but soon moved to [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and then a farm in [[Cherryville, North Carolina]] at 1 year old. In the 5th grade, he moved to [[Gastonia, North Carolina]] where he would later graduate high school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020828063850/http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/092299/dsr_0922bizk.html|title=Jacksonville.com: No. 1 son 09/22/99|date=2002-08-28|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Cepeda|first=Raquel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KFUyjave3gUC&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=fred+durst+cherryville&source=bl&ots=ov9Cr5K2ZW&sig=ACfU3U1mFR0VTvYGNMex8m8ERfDUsodYLw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiEldPNkvPnAhWIVN8KHf1BBAIQ6AEwDHoECA8QAQ#v=onepage&q=fred%20durst%20cherryville&f=false|title=And It Don't Stop: The Best American Hip-Hop Journalism of the Last 25 Years|date=2004-09-29|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-1-4668-1046-4|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shelbystar.com/article/20130523/lifestyle/305239773|title=Limp Bizkit's Fred Durst reflects on growing up in Cherryville and Gastonia|last=Media|first=Bernie Petit / Halifax|website=Shelby Star|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> At the age of 12, Durst took an interest in [[breakdancing]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[punk rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]]. He began to [[rapping|rap]], [[skateboard|skate]], [[beatboxing|beatbox]] and deejay. Leaving the Navy after just two years (1988-1990), Durst moved back to Jacksonville with his father where he worked as a landscaper and a tattoo artist while developing an idea for a band that combined elements of [[rock music|rock]] and hip-hop.<ref name=Devenish1>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/1 1\u201320] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/fred-durst-p240084/biography |title=Fred Durst Biography |author=Ankeny, Jason |website=Allmusic |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Formation of Limp Bizkit (1994\u20131998)===\n{{see also|Limp Bizkit|Limp Bizkit discography}}\n\nIn 1994, Durst, Malachi Sage bassist [[Sam Rivers (bassist)|Sam Rivers]], and Rivers' cousin [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]] jammed together and wrote three songs. Guitarist [[Wes Borland]] later joined. Durst named the band Limp Bizkit because he wanted a name that would repel listeners.<ref name=Devenish21>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/21 21\u201351] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/21 }}</ref> Limp Bizkit developed a cult following in the underground music scene when its covers of [[George Michael]]'s \"[[Faith (George Michael song)|Faith]]\" and [[Paula Abdul]]'s \"[[Straight Up (Paula Abdul song)|Straight Up]]\" began to attract curious concertgoers.<ref name=Devenish21/>\n\nLater, when [[Korn]] performed in town as the opening act for [[Sick of It All]], Durst invited Korn to his house. He was able to persuade bassist [[Reginald Arvizu]] to listen to demos of the songs \"Pollution\", \"[[Counterfeit (song)|Counterfeit]]\", and \"Stuck\". Korn added a then-unsigned Limp Bizkit to two tours, which gave the band a new audience.<ref name=Devenish21/><ref name=\"amg\">{{cite web |last=Bush |first=John |title=Limp Bizkit&nbsp;\u2013 Biography |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p213327/biography|pure_url=yes}} |website=Allmusic |year=2006 |accessdate=January 27, 2008}}</ref> [[DJ Lethal]], formerly of the [[hip hop music|hip hop]] group [[House of Pain]], joined the band as a [[turntablist]]; Durst's disagreements with Borland led the guitarist to quit and rejoin the band.<ref name=Devenish21/>\n\nIn 1997, Limp Bizkit signed with [[Flip Records (1994)|Flip Records]], a subsidiary of [[Interscope Records]], and released their debut album, ''[[Three Dollar Bill, Y'all]]'' to minimal response. Durst was appointed Senior Vice President of A&R at Interscope.<ref name=Devenish127>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/127 127\u2013153] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/127 }}</ref> On October 23, 1997, Durst met the band [[Staind]], but friction quickly emerged between the two over the cover art of Staind's album. Durst unsuccessfully attempted to remove Staind from a concert bill shortly before their performance, but after hearing the band play,<ref name=Devenish127/> he was so impressed that he signed them to Flip/Elektra, recorded a demo with the band, and co-produced their next album, ''[[Dysfunction (album)|Dysfunction]]''.<ref name=Devenish127/>\n\nAfter Limp Bizkit finished a tour with the band [[Deftones]], Durst and DJ Lethal were asked by [[Max Cavalera]], formerly of the band [[Sepultura]], to appear on \"Bleed\", a song from the [[Soulfly (album)|self-titled debut]] of his new band [[Soulfly]]. Cavalera stated that producer Ross Robinson recommended that he work with Durst.<ref name=Devenish51>{{cite book |last1=Devenish |first1=Colin |title=Limp Bizkit |year=2000 |publisher=St. Martin's |isbn=0-312-26349-X |pages=[https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/51 51\u201378] |url=https://archive.org/details/limpbizkit0000deve/page/51 }}</ref> Durst also made an appearance on Korn's album ''[[Follow the Leader (Korn album)|Follow the Leader]]''. [[Jonathan Davis]] had intended to write a [[battle rap]] with [[B-Real]] of [[Cypress Hill]], but the latter's label wouldn't let him do it, and Durst was tapped instead.<ref name=Devenish51/> Davis and Durst wrote the lyrics for \"[[All in the Family (song)|All in the Family]]\", which featured the two vocalists trading insults. Davis and Durst would often offer suggestions for each other's lyrics; a lyric written by Durst as \"tootin' on your bagpipe\" was changed to \"fagpipes\" by Davis, who stated \"I helped him bag on me better\".<ref name=Devenish51/>\n\nDurst began to take an interest in filmmaking, directing the music video for Limp Bizkit's single \"[[Faith (George Michael song)|Faith]]\" in promotion for its appearance in the film ''[[Very Bad Things]]''; he was unsatisfied with it and made a second video which paid tribute to tour mates [[Primus (band)|Primus]], Deftones and [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], who appeared in the video.<ref name=Devenish51/>\n\n===Mainstream success and controversies (1998\u20132005)===\n[[File:Fred Durst.jpg|thumb|175px|right|Durst with Limp Bizkit at [[Sonisphere Festival|Sonisphere 2011]]]]\n\nLimp Bizkit achieved mainstream success with the albums ''[[Significant Other (album)|Significant Other]]'' (1999) and ''[[Chocolate Starfish and the Hot Dog Flavored Water]]'' (2000). In the summer of 1999, Limp Bizkit played at the highly anticipated [[Woodstock '99]] festival in front of approximately 200,000 people. Violence occurred during and after their performance, including fans tearing plywood from the walls during the song \"[[Break Stuff]]\". Several [[sexual assault]]s were reported in the aftermath of the concert.<ref name=\"amg\"/><ref name=Devenish127/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/daily/july99/woodstock29.htm |title=Police Investigate Reports of Rapes at Woodstock |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=July 29, 1999 |accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref> Durst stated during the concert, \"People are getting hurt. Don't let anybody get hurt. But I don't think you should mellow out. That's what [[Alanis Morissette]] had you motherfuckers do. If someone falls, pick 'em up. We already let the negative energy out. Now we wanna let out the positive energy\".<ref name=Devenish127/> Durst later stated in an interview, \"I didn't see anybody getting hurt. You don't see that. When you're looking out on a sea of people and the stage is twenty feet in the air and you're performing, and you're feeling your music, how do they expect us to see something bad going on?\"<ref name=Devenish127/> [[Les Claypool]] told the ''San Francisco Examiner'', \"Woodstock was just Durst being Durst. His attitude is 'no press is bad press', so he brings it on himself. He wallows in it. Still, he's a great guy.\"<ref name=Devenish127/>\n\nIn June 2000, Limp Bizkit performed at the [[WNYL (FM)|WXRK]] [[Dysfunctional Family Picnic]], but showed up an hour late for their set.<ref name=Manning>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427590/limp-creed-trade-barbs-at-krock-show.jhtml |title=Limp, Creed Trade Barbs at KROCK Show |author=Manning, Kara |date=June 26, 2000 |work= |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> An Interscope spokesman stated that there was confusion over the band's set time.<ref name=Manning/> During the band's performance, Durst criticized [[Creed (band)|Creed]] singer [[Scott Stapp]], calling him \"an egomaniac\".<ref name=Manning/> Creed's representatives later presented Durst with an autographed anger management manual during an appearance on ''[[Total Request Live]]''.<ref name=Manning/> In the summer, Limp Bizkit's tour was sponsored by the controversial [[file sharing]] service [[Napster]]. Durst was an outspoken advocate of file sharing.<ref name=\"amg\"/>\n\nDuring the 2000 [[MTV Video Music Award]]s, Durst performed Limp Bizkit's song \"Livin' It Up\", as a duet with [[Christina Aguilera]]. In response to the performance, [[Filter (band)|Filter]] frontman [[Richard Patrick]] claimed that \"Fred getting onstage with Christina Aguilera embarrassed us all.\"<ref name=MTVNewsAguilera/> In response to the negative reactions to the performance, Durst remarked, \"I already told you guys before, [[Nookie (song)|I did it all for the nookie]], man.\"<ref name=MTVNewsAguilera>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1424786/20001003/aguilera_christina.jhtml |title=Limp's Durst Explains Aguilera Duet |author= |date=October 3, 2000 |work= |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> Aguilera, in response to Durst's remark, commented, \"He got no nookie.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1424784/20001010/aguilera_christina.jhtml |title=Aguilera Responds To Durst's \"Nookie\" Comment |author= |date=October 10, 2000 |work= |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring a 2001 tour of Australia at the [[Big Day Out]] festival in Sydney, fans rushed the stage in the [[moshing|mosh pit]], and teenager [[Jessica Michalik]] died of [[asphyxiation]]. In Auckland(New Zealand), on the same tour, Durst threw water over the head of a security personnel tasked with diffusing a similar situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/doublej/music-reads/features/how-the-big-day-out-lost-its-innocence/11606956|title='I had her hand, then I let it go': the Big Day Out loses its innocence|last=By Paul Donoughue|first=Gabrielle Burke and Mike Williams|date=2019-10-17|website=Double J|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> During the Big Day Out crush, Durst has been accused of taunting security guards intervening in the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/77648/report-critical-of-bizkit-in-big-day-out-death|title=Report Critical Of Bizkit In Big Day Out Death|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> In court, Durst, represented by his long-time attorney, Ed McPherson, testified he had warned the concert's organizers Aaron Jackson, Will Pearce and Amar Tailor and promoter Vivian Lees of the potential dangers of such minimal security.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1148637.stm | work=BBC News | title=Limp Bizkit 'devastated' by fan death | date=February 1, 2001 | accessdate=April 4, 2010}}</ref> After viewing video and hearing witness testimony, the coroner said it was evident that the density of the crowd was dangerous at the time Limp Bizkit took the stage and Durst should have acted more responsibly when the problem became apparent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458584/aussie-court-easy-on-bizkit.jhtml |title=Organizers Blamed in Limp Bizkit Mosh-Pit Death |author=D'Angelo, Joe |date=November 8, 2002 |work= |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> Durst stated that he was \"emotionally scarred\" because of the teenager's death.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/17/1023864403550.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Limp Bizkit singer tells of emotional scars from Big Day Out tragedy | date=June 18, 2002 | first=Lee | last=Glendinning}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Durst was tapped to write songs for [[Britney Spears]], and later said that he was in a relationship with her. Spears denied Durst's claims.<ref name=Jacks/> In a 2009 interview, he explained that \"I just guess at the time it was taboo for a guy like me to be associated with a gal like her.\"<ref name=Jacks>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1607309/20090319/spears_britney.jhtml|title=Fred Durst Looks Back at His Relationship With Britney Spears|date=March 19, 2009|accessdate=2010-06-06|last=Jacks|first=Brian|publisher=MTV}}</ref> In February 2005, a sex tape featuring Durst was released on the Internet. Durst filed a $70 million lawsuit against ten websites that posted the video.<ref>{{cite web|first=Corey|last=Moss|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1497523/20050225/limp_bizkit.jhtml?headlines=true|title=Fred Durst Says Sex Video Stolen From His PC|publisher=MTV|date=February 25, 2005|accessdate=2008-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-03-08-fred-durst-lawsuit_x.htm|title=Limp Bizkit rocker sues over Web sex tape|agency=Associated Press|work=[[USA Today]]|date=March 9, 2005|accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, Limp Bizkit participated on the [[Summer Sanitarium Tour]], headlined by [[Metallica]].<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Montgomery |title=Mudvayne Lose The Makeup, Find Inspiration in Isolation |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1497672/03022005/mudvayne.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=March 2, 2005 |accessdate=January 5, 2009 }}</ref> In the days preceding the tour's stop in [[Chicago]], local radio personality [[Mancow Muller]] mocked Durst and suggested that listeners who were attending the concert should heckle the singer and throw debris.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Susman |first=Gary |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,471517,00.html |title=Throw Stuff |magazine=EW.com |date=July 29, 2003 |accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref> With the crowd chanting \"fuck Fred Durst\" and pelting the stage with garbage, Durst erupted in a profane, homophobic tirade after six songs, threw the microphone down and walked off stage.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman |first=Gil |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1474912/20030728/limp_bizkit.jhtml |title=Limp Bizkit Walk Offstage After Chicago Crowd Gets Hostile \u2013 Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=July 28, 2003 |accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref> Durst was eventually sued for breach of contract (for not completing the show) by Chicago lawyer Michael Young in a [[class-action suit]].<ref name=\"bbc099\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3178492.stm |title=Fans sue Limp Bizkit over walkout |date=October 9, 2003 |work=BBC News |accessdate=May 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005, ''[[The Unquestionable Truth (Part 1)]]'' was released. [[Sammy Siegler]] took over drumming duties for the band for much of the album. At Durst's insistence, the album was released as an underground album, without any advertising or promotion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1514094/20051118/limp_bizkit.jhtml |title=Music Ruined Wes Borland's Life, So He's Formed A New Band |last1=Harris |first1=Chris |date=November 18, 2005 |work= |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 14, 2011}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1526158/borland-casts-doubt-on-limp-bizkits-future.jhtml |title=Bye Bye Bizkit? Wes Borland Says Limp Are Pretty Much Done |last1=Harris |first1=Chris |date=March 17, 2006 |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 14, 2011}}</ref> The album sold over 2,000,000 copies worldwide, peaking at number 24 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/l/limp_bizkit/news_feature_052305/ |title=Limp Bizkit: What Happened? |last1=Moss |first1=Corey|date= |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=December 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=AllmusicCharts>{{cite web |url=https://allmusic.com/artist/limp-bizkit-p213327/charts-awards |title=Limp Bizkit \u2013 Charts & Awards |website=Allmusic |accessdate=December 14, 2011}}</ref> Durst later announced that despite the album's title, no sequel to ''The Unquestionable Truth'' would be produced.<ref name=ErlewineGoldCobra>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/gold-cobra-r2210421/review |title=''Gold Cobra'' \u2013 Limp Bizkit |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |website=Allmusic |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> Later in the year, the band released a ''[[Greatest Hitz (Limp Bizkit album)|Greatest Hitz]]'' album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moss |first=Corey |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1512963/11032005/limp_bizkit.jhtml |title=Fred Durst Says Limp Bizkit Are About To Bring on the Gravy \u2013 Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=November 3, 2005 |accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHaving been bullied while growing up, Durst disliked seeing people \"using my music as fuel to torture other people\"; feeling that his music was being misinterpreted, he would later cite this as the reason for the band taking a hiatus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Andy |title=Fred Durst: Limp Bizkit Was Used as \"Fuel to Torture Other People\" |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fred-durst-limp-bizkit-was-used-as-fuel-to-torture-other-people-108646/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Fred Durst at the 2008 Tribeca Film Festival.JPG|thumb|160px|right|Durst at the premiere of ''[[Baby Mama (film)|Baby Mama]]'' at the 2008 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]\n\n===Start of film career (2006\u20132009)===\nWhile Limp Bizkit was on hiatus, Durst began working in [[independent film]]s. In 2006, Durst costarred in the film ''[[Population 436]]''. His directorial debut, ''[[The Education of Charlie Banks]]'', was released the following year. The film, which starred [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Chris Marquette]] and [[Jason Ritter]], received mixed reviews; [[Rotten Tomatoes]], a review aggregator, assigned the film a score of 46%. The website's consensus stated, \"Unevenness and earnestness mire this otherwise sweet, surprising coming of age drama.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/education_of_charlie_banks/ |title=''The Education of Charlie Banks'' |work= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> A second directorial effort, ''[[The Longshots]]'', starring [[Ice Cube]] and [[Keke Palmer]], was released in 2008. Rotten Tomatoes assigned the film a score of 39%, with the consensus indicating that the film was \"a largely formulaic affair, rarely deviating from the inspirational sports movie playbook.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/longshots/ |title=''The Longshots'' Tomatometer |author= |date= |work=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> The same year, Durst appeared as a bartender in two episodes of the television medical drama ''[[House (TV series)|House, M.D.]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Michelle|last=Romero|date=May 13, 2008|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20199656,00.html|title='House': Head Case|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=2008-10-17}}</ref>\n\n===Limp Bizkit reunion (2009\u2013present)===\n[[File:Fred Durst performing with Limp Bizkit 2019 (Quintin Soloviev).jpg|thumb|Fred Durst performing with Limp Bizkit at Quebec Agora Fest 2019.]]\n[[File:Fred Durst performing at The Roxy on December 3, 2019 (Quintin Soloviev).jpg|thumb|Fred Durst performing at The Roxy on December 3, 2019]]\nIn 2009, the original lineup of Limp Bizkit reunited and began touring. Durst announced that they had begun to record a new album, ''[[Gold Cobra]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.kerrang.com/2009/11/world_exclusive_limp_bizkit_na.html |title=World exclusive! Limp Bizkit name new album |author=Simon |date=November 30, 2009 |work=Kerrang.com |publisher=Bauer Performance |accessdate=November 30, 2009}}</ref> The album was released on June 28, 2011, receiving mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/gold-cobra |title=''Gold Cobra'' at Metacritic |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 26, 2011}}</ref> It peaked at number 16 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=AllmusicCharts/>\n\nIn 2012, Durst appeared on the [[Insane Clown Posse]] [[cover album]] ''[[Smothered, Covered & Chunked]]'' on a cover of [[AMG (rapper)|AMG]]'s \"[[Bitch Betta Have My Money]]\".<ref>{{youtube|JU8fwgGMiGU|Insane Clown Posse \u2013 The Mighty Death Pop \u2013 Infomercial}}</ref> In February 2012, [[Lil Wayne]] announced in a radio interview that Limp Bizkit had signed to his label, [[Cash Money Records]], which Durst confirmed on his Twitter page.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lil Wayne: Cash Money Signs Limp Biskit|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lil-wayne-cash-money-signs-limp-bizkit-20120224|location=New York | work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> A few months later Durst was featured alongside Lil Wayne and [[Birdman (entertainer)|Birdman]] on the [[Kevin Rudolf]] song \"Champions\", which peaked in the top 10 on [[iTunes]].\n\nOriginally, Durst was to direct and produce the film ''[[Pawn Shop Chronicles]]'', starring [[Paul Walker]];<ref name=Kit>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-walker-star-fred-dursts-98917 |title=Paul Walker to Star in Fred Durst's 'Pawn Shop Chronicles' |author=Kit, Borys |date=February 12, 2011 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> but [[Wayne Kramer (filmmaker)|Wayne Kramer]] was later chosen to direct the film.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/06/matt-dillon-brendan-fraser-elijah-wood-vincent-donofrio-join-wayne-kramers-pawn-shop-chronicles/ |title=Matt Dillon, Brendan Fraser, Elijah Wood, Vincent D'Onofrio Join Wayne Kramer's 'Pawn Shop Chronicles' |magazine=Deadline.com |accessdate=2012-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefilmstage.com/news/wayne-kramer-assembles-huge-cast-for-pawn-shop-chronicles-paz-vega-a-brief-lover-of-almodovar/ |title=Wayne Kramer Assembles Huge Cast for \u2018Pawn Shop Chronicles\u2019; Paz Vega A \u2018Standby Lover\u2019 for Almodovar |publisher=Thefilmstage.com |date=June 4, 2012 |accessdate=2012-09-16}}</ref> In 2014, Durst shot three commercials for the website [[Eharmony]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Childers |first1=Chad |title=LIMP BIZKIT\u2019S FRED DURST DIRECTS HUMOROUS NEW EHARMONY COMMERCIAL |url=https://loudwire.com/limp-bizkit-fred-durst-eharmony-commercials/ |website=Loudwire |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> In February 2018, Durst began filming ''[[The Fanatic (2019 film)|The Fanatic]]'', starring [[John Travolta]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.al.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2018/02/fred_dursts_movie_moose_filmin.html|title=Fred Durst's movie, 'Moose,' filming in Birmingham with star John Travolta|work=AL.com|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nFred Durst has a daughter named Adriana Durst. She was born in 1990 to Durst and his then-wife Rachel Tergesen. He also has a son named Dallas with ex-girlfriend, actress Jennifer Thayer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=123851|title=Limp Bizkit'S Fred Durst Gets Married|publisher=Blabbermouth.Net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/fred-durst/news/durst-slams-press-for-son-mistake|title=Durst Slams Press For Son Mistake|publisher=contactmusic.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Durst married Esther Nazarov and split after three months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fred Durst confirms split with wife of three months, Esther Nazarov, on Twitter|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-09-29/gossip/17931925_1_networking-site-las-vegas-fred-durst | location=New York | work=Daily News|first=Cristina|last=Everett|date=September 29, 2009}}</ref> Durst married his third wife <ref name=\"APDurst\">{{cite web |title=Fred Durst finalizes divorce |url=https://www.apnews.com/8effe2dc3b8347cea7d7c830baca0166 |website=APnews.com |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> make-up artist Kseniya Beryazina <ref name=\"Peopledurst\"/> in 2012.<ref name=\"APDurst\"/> They filed for divorce in September 2018.<ref name=\"Peopledurst\">{{cite web |last1=Zauzmer |first1=Emily |title=Limp Bizkit Frontman Fred Durst Files for Divorce from Kseniya Beryazina: Report |url=https://people.com/music/limp-bizkit-fred-durst-files-divorce-kseniya-beryazina/ |website=People |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Fred Durst stated his interest in obtaining a Russian passport and spending half of the year in [[Crimea]].<ref name=BB151009>{{cite news |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6722889/fred-durst-films-russia-crimea |title= Fred Durst Wants to Make Films for the 'Great Future' of Russia and Annexed Crimea |first= Vladimir |last= Kozlov |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= October 9, 2015 }}</ref> He wrote a letter in which he stated that [[Vladimir Putin]] is \"a great guy with clear moral principles and a nice person.\"<ref name=RFE151021>{{cite news |url= http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-separatists-ready-for-limp-bizkit/27318706.html |title= DNR Ready For Limp Bizkit And Its 'Hot Dog Flavored Water' |first= Anna |last= Shamanska |work= [[Radio Free Europe]] |date= October 21, 2015 }}</ref> Following that, Durst was banned by the [[Security Service of Ukraine]] from entering Ukraine for five years \"in the interests of guaranteeing the security\" of the country.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/35155170/limp-bizkits-fred-durst-is-banned-from-ukraine-for-five-years-for-security-reasons |title= Limp Bizkit's Fred Durst is banned from Ukraine for five years for security reasons |publisher= [[BBC]] |date= December 21, 2015}}</ref> Soon thereafter, all Limp Bizkit sales on the territory of Ukraine were prohibited.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6814192/limp-bizkit-fred-durst-banned-ukraine |title= Limp Bizkit's Fred Durst Banned by Ukrainian Government: Reports |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= December 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018 California wildfires]], Durst's house burned down. His bandmate, Wes Borland, also lost several pieces of equipment in the fire. These were stored in Durst's house as they were scheduled to record the day after the fire.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharp |first1=Tyler |title=LIMP BIZKIT FRONTMAN FRED DURST\u2019S HOUSE BURNS DOWN IN CALIFORNIA FIRES |url=https://loudwire.com/limp-bizkit-fred-durst-house-burn-down-california-fires/ |website=Loudwire |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, Durst is a [[vegan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.flipboard.com/inside-flipboard/on-the-red-couch-with-musician-fred-durst|title=On the Red Couch with Musician Fred Durst|date=March 16, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Feuds===\nDurst was accused of insulting fans of the band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] in 1999 by referring to them as \"fat, ugly kids\". Slipknot singer [[Corey Taylor]] responded during a concert in New York by claiming that the fans of Slipknot \"for the most part, enjoy all kinds of music, like Limp Bizkit, maybe.\" Taylor went on to claim that insulting the fans of Slipknot could also be insulting the fans of Limp Bizkit themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1431271/slipknot-has-issues-to-discuss-with-limps-durst/|title=Slipknot Feud|date=1999-12-09|website=MTV|access-date=2016-02-11}}</ref> In a later interview, Corey mentions Durst is a good business man, but he is not an artist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9TU8rIw6FA&t=141s|title=Slipknot Feud|date=1999-12-09|website=YouTube|access-date=2018-08-05}}</ref> Corey also mentioned that it is not because of him as a person but it was because of what he was doing, which he claimed was because he was \"processing music that other kids feel.\"\n\nDurst also fell out with rapper and former friend [[Eminem]] regarding Eminem's feud with [[Everlast (musician)|Everlast]]. This resulted in Eminem creating a [[diss track]] against Durst called \"Girls\" released on his [[D12]] group's 2001 album ''[[Devil's Night (album)|Devil's Night]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/uk/eminem-vs-everybody-a-list-of-slim-shady-diss-songs-104112|title=Eminem vs. everybody: A list of Slim Shady diss songs|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, 2018, [[Shaggy 2 Dope]] from the band [[Insane Clown Posse]] attempted to dropkick Durst during their performance of the song \"Faith\". [[DJ Lethal]] from [[Limp Bizkit]] responded on [[Instagram]] Live calling Shaggy a \"clout chaser\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WlGZzMrV0F4&t=42s|title=Fred Durst attacked by Shaggy 2 Dope|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n;Limp Bizkit\n* ''[[Three Dollar Bill, Y'all|Three Dollar Bill, Y'all$]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Significant Other (album)|Significant Other]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Chocolate Starfish and the Hot Dog Flavored Water]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Results May Vary]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[The Unquestionable Truth (Part 1)]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Gold Cobra]]'' (2011)\n===Singles===\n===As lead artist===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles, with selected chart positions and certifications, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"11\" | Peak chart positions\n!\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\" | [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br /><ref name=\"US-singles\">{{cite web | url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=limp bizkit|chart=Hot 100}} | title=Limp Bizkit \u2013 Chart History: Hot 100 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Alternative Songs|US<br>Alt.]]<br /><ref name=\"US-Alternative-singles\">{{cite web | url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=limp bizkit|chart=Alternative Songs}} | title=Limp Bizkit \u2013 Chart History: Alternative Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|US<br>Main. Rock]]<br /><ref name=\"US-Mainstream-Rock-singles\">{{cite web | url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=limp bizkit|chart=Mainstream Rock Tracks}} | title=Limp Bizkit \u2013 Chart History: Mainstream Rock Tracks | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref>\n! scop