{"title_page": "Fulham Road Jewish Cemetery", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Fulham Road Jewish Cemetery\n| image       = Jewish Cemetery, Fulham Road - geograph.org.uk - 1305738.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = The cemetery\n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1815\n| country     = England\n| location    = Fulham Road ([[London Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]), London SW3\n| type        = [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]]\n| style       = \n| owner       = Western Charitable Foundation\n| size        = {{convert|1|acre|ha}}\n| graves      = \n| interments  = \n| website     = [http://www.westerncharitablefoundation.com/cemeteries/ Official website]\n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2359125/brompton-jewish-cemetery Brompton Jewish Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\nThe '''Fulham Road Jewish Cemetery''' (also called Fulham Cemetery<ref name=\"Western\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.westerncharitablefoundation.com/cemeteries/ |title=Cemeteries |website=Western Charitable Foundation |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> and formerly known as the '''Brompton Jewish Cemetery''')<ref name='LGO'/> is a Jewish cemetery on [[Fulham Road]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]. A locked door  on the Fulham Road serves as the entrance to the cemetery, otherwise it is not visible from the street. The cemetery is overlooked by the blocks of flats that surround it.\n\nAsh and plane trees are planted at the cemetery, which is {{convert|1|acre|ha}} in size.<ref name='P&G'>{{cite web|title=Western Synagogue Cemetery, Kensington|url=https://www.parksandgardens.org/places/western-synagogue-cemetery-kensington|publisher=Parks & Gardens UK|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BardMiles2017\">{{cite book|author1=Bard, Robert|author2=Miles, Adrian|title=London's Hidden Burial Grounds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G0AsDgAAQBAJ|date=15 February 2017|publisher=[[Amberley Publishing]]|isbn=978-1-4456-6112-4|page=106}}</ref> It has been described as a \"tiny\" cemetery that is \"totally unexpected in the Fulham Road\" and creates an impression \"more typical of Prague than London\".<ref name = \"Meller213\">{{cite book|authors= Meller, Hugh; Parsons, Brian|title= London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer|publisher= [[The History Press]]|date= 2008 |page = 213|ISBN=978-0-7509-4622-3}}</ref>\n\nThe cemetery is owned by the Western Charitable Foundation,<ref name=\"Owners\">{{Cite news |url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/owners-say-theres-no-proposed-sale-of-small-jewish-cemetery-in-chelsea/ |title=Owners say there\u2019s \u2018no proposed sale\u2019 of small Jewish cemetery in Chelsea |date=25 January 2019 |work=[[Jewish News]] |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> and is open only by appointment.\n\n==History==\nIt was opened in 1815 as the burial ground for the [[Western Synagogue]], now [[Western Marble Arch Synagogue]].<ref name=\"Fears\">{{Cite news |last=Rocker |first=Simon |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/western-charitable-foundation-quells-fears-about-sale-of-fulham-road-cemetery-1.457534 |title=Western Charitable Foundation quells fears about sale of Fulham Road Cemetery |date=26 January 2018 |work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> The site was purchased in December 1815 for \u00a3400.<ref name='LGO'>{{cite web|title=Western Synagogue Cemetery| url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=KAC148|work=London Gardens Online|accessdate=21 April 2020|publisher = [[London Parks and Gardens Trust]]}}</ref> An office building and prayer hall originally stood near the entrance. The cemetery closed in 1885 although burials in reserved plots continued until 1910.<ref name='P&G'/>\n\nIt was the first Jewish burial ground west of the [[City of London]]. It was restored in 1898 funded by a Mr Ellis Franklin, whose parents were buried here, with the maintenance of the cemetery funded by \u00a320,000 from the estate of Adel Hopkins (n\u00e9e Rootstein). The Edmonton cemetery was subsequently established by the Western Synagogue in 1884.<ref name='P&G'/>\n\n==Notable burials==\n* [[Herschell Filipowski]] (1816\u20131872), [[Lithuania]]n-born  [[Hebraist]], editor, [[Mathematics|mathematician]], [[Linguistics|linguist]] and [[actuary]]<ref name=\"FILIPOWSKI\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/getperson.php?personID=I3736&tree=Cemeteries |title=FILIPOWSKI (PHILLIPS) Herschell |website=Cemetery Scribes |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Solomon Hart]] (1806\u20131881), artist and professor of painting at the [[Royal Academy]] (RA) from 1854 to 1863. Hart was the first Jewish member of the RA<ref name='LGO'/>\n*[[Zadok Jessel]] (1792\u20131864), businessman and the father of the Master of the Rolls Sir [[George Jessel (jurist)|George Jessel]]<ref name='LGO'/>\n*[[Joseph Waley]] (1818\u20131873), first president of the [[Anglo-Jewish Association]] and professor of political economy at [[London University]]<ref name='LGO'/>\n*[[Simon Waley]] (1827\u20131875), stockbroker, pianist and composer<ref name='LGO'/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jewish cemeteries in the London area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|http://www.westerncharitablefoundation.com/cemeteries/}}\n*[http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/showmap.php?cemeteryID=20&tree=Cemeteries  Cemetery Scribes: Brompton (Fulham Rd) Jewish Cemetery]\n*[https://rbkclocalstudies.wordpress.com/2016/08/18/hidden-in-plain-sight-chelseas-jewish-cemetery/ Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea Local Studies blog \u2013 Hidden in plain sight: Chelsea's Jewish cemetery]\n\n[[Category:1815 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Chelsea, London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Fulham Road Jewish Cemetery\n| image       = Jewish Cemetery, Fulham Road - geograph.org.uk - 1305738.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = The cemetery\n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1815\n| country     = England\n| location    = Fulham Road ([[London Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]), London SW3\n| type        = [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]]\n| style       = \n| owner       = Western Charitable Foundation\n| size        = {{convert|1|acre|ha}}\n| graves      = \n| interments  = \n| website     = [http://www.westerncharitablefoundation.com/cemeteries/ Official website]\n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2359125/brompton-jewish-cemetery Brompton Jewish Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\nThe '''Fulham Road Jewish Cemetery''' (also called Fulham Cemetery<ref name=\"Western\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.westerncharitablefoundation.com/cemeteries/ |title=Cemeteries |website=Western Charitable Foundation |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> and formerly known as the '''Brompton Jewish Cemetery''')<ref name='LGO'/> is a Jewish cemetery on [[Fulham Road]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]. A locked door  on the Fulham Road serves as the entrance to the cemetery, otherwise it is not visible from the street. The cemetery is overlooked by the blocks of flats that surround it.\n\nAsh and plane trees are planted at the cemetery, which is {{convert|1|acre|ha}} in size.<ref name='P&G'>{{cite web|title=Western Synagogue Cemetery, Kensington|url=https://www.parksandgardens.org/places/western-synagogue-cemetery-kensington|publisher=Parks & Gardens UK|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BardMiles2017\">{{cite book|author1=Bard, Robert|author2=Miles, Adrian|title=London's Hidden Burial Grounds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G0AsDgAAQBAJ|date=15 February 2017|publisher=[[Amberley Publishing]]|isbn=978-1-4456-6112-4|page=106}}</ref> It has been described as a \"tiny\" cemetery that is \"totally unexpected in the Fulham Road\" and creates an impression \"more typical of Prague than London\".<ref name = \"Meller213\">{{cite book|authors= Meller, Hugh; Parsons, Brian|title= London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer|publisher= [[The History Press]]|date= 2008 |page = 213|ISBN=978-0-7509-4622-3}}</ref>\n\nThe cemetery is owned by the Western Charitable Foundation,<ref name=\"Owners\">{{Cite news |url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/owners-say-theres-no-proposed-sale-of-small-jewish-cemetery-in-chelsea/ |title=Owners say there\u2019s \u2018no proposed sale\u2019 of small Jewish cemetery in Chelsea |date=25 January 2019 |work=[[Jewish News]] |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> and is open only by appointment.\n\n==History==\nIt was opened in 1815 as the burial ground for the [[Western Synagogue]], now [[Western Marble Arch Synagogue]].<ref name=\"Fears\">{{Cite news |last=Rocker |first=Simon |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/western-charitable-foundation-quells-fears-about-sale-of-fulham-road-cemetery-1.457534 |title=Western Charitable Foundation quells fears about sale of Fulham Road Cemetery |date=26 January 2018 |work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> The site was purchased in December 1815 for \u00a3400.<ref name='LGO'>{{cite web|title=Western Synagogue Cemetery| url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=KAC148|work=London Gardens Online|accessdate=21 April 2020|publisher = [[London Parks and Gardens Trust]]}}</ref> An office building and prayer hall originally stood near the entrance. The cemetery closed in 1885 although burials in reserved plots continued until 1910.<ref name='P&G'/>\n\nIt was the first Jewish burial ground west of the [[City of London]]. It was restored in 1898 funded by a Mr Ellis Franklin, whose parents were buried here, with the maintenance of the cemetery funded by \u00a320,000 from the estate of Adel Hopkins (n\u00e9e Rootstein). The Edmonton cemetery was subsequently established by the Western Synagogue in 1884.<ref name='P&G'/>\n\n==Notable burials==\n* [[Herschell Filipowski]] (1816\u20131872),[[Lithuania]]n-born  [[Hebraist]], editor, [[Mathematics|mathematician]], [[Linguistics|linguist]] and [[actuary]]<ref name=\"FILIPOWSKI\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/getperson.php?personID=I3736&tree=Cemeteries |title=FILIPOWSKI (PHILLIPS) Herschell |website=Cemetery Scribes |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Solomon Hart]] (1806\u20131881), artist and professor of painting at the [[Royal Academy]] (RA) from 1854 to 1863. Hart was the first Jewish member of the RA<ref name='LGO'/>\n*[[Zadok Jessel]] (1792\u20131864), businessman and the father of the Master of the Rolls Sir [[George Jessel (jurist)|George Jessel]]<ref name='LGO'/>\n*[[Joseph Waley]] (1818\u20131873), first president of the [[Anglo-Jewish Association]] and professor of political economy at [[London University]]<ref name='LGO'/>\n*[[Simon Waley]] (1827\u20131875), stockbroker, pianist and composer<ref name='LGO'/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jewish cemeteries in the London area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|http://www.westerncharitablefoundation.com/cemeteries/}}\n*[http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/showmap.php?cemeteryID=20&tree=Cemeteries  Cemetery Scribes: Brompton (Fulham Rd) Jewish Cemetery]\n*[https://rbkclocalstudies.wordpress.com/2016/08/18/hidden-in-plain-sight-chelseas-jewish-cemetery/ Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea Local Studies blog \u2013 Hidden in plain sight: Chelsea's Jewish cemetery]\n\n[[Category:1815 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Chelsea, London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]