n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Chicago Midway International Airport\n| image = Midway_International_Airport_Logo.svg\n| image2 = Midway Airport Airfield.jpg\n| image-width = \n| image2-width = \n| IATA = MDW\n| ICAO = KMDW\n| FAA = MDW\n| WMO = 72534\n| type = Public\n| owner = City of Chicago\n| operator = Chicago Department of Aviation\n| city-served = [[Chicago metropolitan area]]\n| location = [[Clearing, Chicago|Clearing]] and [[Garfield Ridge, Chicago|Garfield Ridge]], [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| opened = {{Start date and age|1927|12|12}}<ref name=\"encyclopediaofchicago\"/>\n| focus_city = [[Southwest Airlines]]\n| elevation-f = 620\n| elevation-m = 189\n| website = [https://www.flychicago.com/midway/home/pages/default.aspx https://www.flychicago.com/midway/]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|47|10|N|87|45|09|W|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n| image_map = KMDW Airport Map.png\n| image_map_caption = [[FAA]] airport diagram\n| pushpin_map = Chicago#USA Illinois#USA\n| pushpin_label = '''MDW'''\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Chicago\n| r1-number = 4L/22R\n| r1-length-f = 5,507\n| r1-length-m = 1,679\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| r2-number = 4R/22L\n| r2-length-f = 6,445\n| r2-length-m = 1,964\n| r2-surface = Asphalt/Concrete\n| r3-number = 13C/31C\n| r3-length-f = 6,522\n| r3-length-m = 1,988\n| r3-surface = Concrete\n| r4-number = 13L/31R\n| r4-length-f = 5,141\n| r4-length-m = 1,567\n| r4-surface = Asphalt\n| r5-number = 13R/31L\n| r5-length-f = 3,859\n| r5-length-m = 1,176\n| r5-surface = Concrete\n| stat-year = 2019\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data = 232,084\n| stat2-header = Passenger volume\n| stat2-data = 20,844,860\n| stat3-header = Cargo tonnage\n| stat3-data = 19,348.5\n| footnotes = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]]<ref name=FAA>{{FAA-airport|ID=MDW|use=PU|own=PU|site=04508.*A}}. effective October 17, 2013.</ref> and airport website<ref name=CAS>{{cite web |url=https://www.flychicago.com/business/CDA/factsfigures/Pages/airtraffic.aspx |title=Air Traffic Data |publisher=Chicago Department of Aviation |date=December 2018 |accessdate=April 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914012140/https://www.flychicago.com/business/CDA/factsfigures/Pages/airtraffic.aspx |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Chicago Midway International Airport''' {{airport codes|MDW|KMDW|MDW}}, typically referred to as '''Midway Airport''', '''Chicago Midway''', or simply '''Midway''', is a major commercial [[airport]] on the south side of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], located eight miles (13&nbsp;km) from the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]]. Established in 1927, Midway served as Chicago's primary airport until the opening of [[O'Hare International Airport]] in 1955. Today, Midway is the second-largest airport in [[Chicago metropolitan area]] and the state of Illinois, serving 20,844,860 passengers in 2019.<ref name=\"CAS\" /> Traffic is currently dominated by [[low-cost carrier]] [[Southwest Airlines]]; Chicago is Southwest's largest [[focus city]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://swamedia.com/channels/Corporate-Fact-Sheet/pages/corporate-fact-sheet#top10 |title = Southwest/AirTran Top Ten Airports by Departures |publisher = Southwest Airlines |date = August 2013 |accessdate = November 12, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161012025536/http://swamedia.com/channels/Corporate-Fact-Sheet/pages/corporate-fact-sheet#top10 |archive-date = October 12, 2016 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>Schulte, Sarah. \"[http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=8051631 SWA flights take off at Midway, airline's largest hub] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112004258/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news%2Flocal&id=8051631 |date=November 12, 2013 }}.\" ''[[WLS-TV]]''. April 4, 2011. Retrieved on April 4, 2011.</ref>\n\nOriginally named '''Chicago Municipal Airport''', it was renamed to honor the [[Battle of Midway]]. The now-defunct [[Midway Airlines (1976-1991)|Midway Airlines]] that once serviced the airport took its name from the airport, not vice versa. The airfield is located in a square mile bounded by [[55th Street (Chicago)|55th]] and 63rd Streets, and Central and [[Cicero Avenue]]s. The current terminal complex was completed in 2001. The terminal bridges Cicero Avenue and contains 43 gates with facilities for international passengers. [[Stevenson Expressway]] ([[Interstate 55|I-55]]) and the [[Chicago Transit Authority|CTA]] [[Orange Line (Chicago Transit Authority)|Orange Line]] provide freeway and rapid transit access to [[Chicago Loop|The Loop]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history (1923\u20131962)===\nOriginally named '''Chicago Air Park''',<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|url=http://destinations.usatoday.com/chicago/transportation/ |title=Chicago Transportation: Chicago Midway Airport |work=USA Today |date=May 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070102194813/http://destinations.usatoday.com/chicago/transportation/ |archivedate=January 2, 2007 }}</ref> Midway Airport was built on a {{convert|320|acre|adj=on}} plot in 1923 with one [[cinder]] runway mainly for [[airmail]] flights. In 1926 the city leased the airport and named it '''Chicago Municipal Airport''' on December 12, 1927.<ref name=\"encyclopediaofchicago\">{{cite web | url =http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/828.html | title =Midway Airport | publisher =Encyclopedia of Chicago | access-date =August 16, 2012 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120814070335/http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/828.html | archive-date =August 14, 2012 | url-status =live }}</ref> By 1928, the airport had twelve hangars and four runways, lit for night operations.<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nA major fire early on June 25, 1930, destroyed two hangars and 27 aircraft, \"12 of them tri-motor passenger planes.\" The loss was estimated at more than two million dollars. The hangars destroyed were of the [[Universal Air Lines Corporation|Universal Air Lines, Inc.]], and the Grey Goose Airlines, the latter under lease to [[Stout Air Services|Stout Air Lines]]. The fire followed an explosion of undetermined cause in the Universal hangar.<ref>Associated Press, \"27 Planes Burn In Chicago Fire\", ''Sarasota Herald'', Sarasota, Florida, Wednesday 25 June 1930, Volume 5, Number 224, page one.</ref>\n\n[[File:Midway chicago.jpg|thumb|right|The Chicago area, featuring Chicago Midway and [[O'Hare International Airport|O'Hare]] International Airports]]\nIn 1931 a new passenger terminal opened at 62nd St;<ref name=\"history\" /> the following year the airport claimed to be the \"[[World's busiest airport|World's Busiest]]\" with over 100,846 passengers on 60,947 flights.<ref name=\"visitorsguide\">{{cite web | url =http://www.flychicago.com/news/pdf/MDWVisitorsGuide2005Revised.pdf | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080414001228/http://www.flychicago.com/news/pdf/MDWVisitorsGuide2005Revised.pdf | archivedate =April 14, 2008| title = Midway Airport Visitors Guide (History Section) | publisher=FlyChicago.com | date = May 12, 2007}}</ref> (The July 1932 [[Official Airline Guide|Official Aviation Guide]] (OAG) shows 206 scheduled airline departures a week.)\n\nMore construction was funded in part by $1&nbsp;million from the [[Works Progress Administration]]; the airport expanded to fill the square mile in 1938\u201341 after a court ordered the [[Chicago and Western Indiana Railroad]] to reroute tracks that had crossed the square along the northern edge of the older field.\n\nThe March 1939 OAG shows 47 weekday departures: 13 on United, 13 American, 9 TWA, 4 Northwest, and two each on Eastern, Braniff, [[Capital Airlines (United States)|Pennsylvania Central]], and [[Chicago and Southern Air Lines|C&S]].<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |year=1939 |title=Official Aviation Guide |publisher= Official Aviation Guide Company |location=Chicago IL |page= |url= |accessdate= }}</ref> New York's airport (Newark, then LaGuardia by the end of 1939) was then the busiest airline airport in the United States, but Midway passed LaGuardia in 1948 and kept the title until 1960.<ref name=\"history\" /> The record-breaking [[1945 Japan\u2013Washington flight]] of B-29s refueled at the airport on their way to Washington DC.\n\nIn July 1949 the airport was renamed after the [[Battle of Midway]].<ref name=\"visitorsguide\" /> That year Midway saw 3.2&nbsp;million passengers; passengers peaked at 10 million in 1959.<ref>This [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cm66qtg65DY video of Chicago Midway Airport in 1954] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130142028/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cm66qtg65DY |date=November 30, 2015 }} shows the increase in traffic that Midway Airport experienced during the 1950s.{{cite web| url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cm66qtg65DY| title =Chicago Midway Airport \u2013 1954| publisher =YouTube| date =December 2, 2007| access-date =November 20, 2015| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20151130142028/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cm66qtg65DY| archive-date =November 30, 2015| url-status =live}}</ref> The diagram on the January 1951 C&GS approach chart shows four parallel pairs of runways, all 4240&nbsp;ft or less except for 5730-ft runway 13R (current runway 13C) and 5230-ft runway 4R. Airport diagram for [https://www.flickr.com/photos/12530375@N08/8096614400/sizes/h 1959]\n\nThe April 1957 OAG shows 414 weekday fixed-wing departures from Midway: 83 American, 83 United, 56 TWA, 40 Capital, 35 North Central, 28 Delta, 27 Eastern, 22 Northwest, 19 Ozark, 11 Braniff, 5 Trans-Canada, and 5 Lake Central. Air France, Lufthansa, and REAL (of Brazil) had a few flights per week.<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |year=1957 |title=Official Airline Guide |publisher= American Aviation Publications |location=Washington DC |page= |url= |accessdate= }}</ref> Midway was running out of room and in any case could not handle the 707 and DC-8 jets that appeared in 1959; every Chicago jet flight had to use O'Hare, which had opened to the airlines in 1955. Electras and Viscounts could have continued to fly out of Midway, but O'Hare's new terminal opened in 1962, allowing airlines to consolidate their flights. From July 1962 until United returned in July 1964, Midway's only scheduled airline was Chicago Helicopter. In August 1966 a total of four fixed-wing arrivals were scheduled, all United 727s (United was alone at Midway until early 1968).\n\n===Post-O'Hare reconstruction (1963\u20131993)===\nBy 1967 reconstruction began at the airport, adding three new concourses with 28 gates and three ticket counters,<ref name=\"visitorsguide\" /> and in 1968 the city invested $10&nbsp;million in renovation funds.<ref name=\"history\" /> (For a few months during the 1967 renovation Midway had no scheduled airline flights.) The funds partly supported construction of the [[Stevenson Expressway]], and Midway saw the return of major airlines that year, with 1,663,074 passengers<ref>''Airport Activity Statistics'' shows 208,086 total enplanements in 1968.</ref> on smaller-capacity, shorter range twin-jet and [[trijet]] airliners such as the [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]], [[BAC One-Eleven]], [[Boeing 727]], and [[Boeing 737]] that could use Midway's runways, which the [[Boeing 707]] and [[Douglas DC-8]] could not. In May 1968 there were 22 scheduled departures: six United 727s to MSP, DCA and LGA, 12 Northwest 727s to MSP and CLE, one Delta DC-9 to STL and three Ozark FH227s.\n\nThe December 1970 OAG shows 86 weekday arrivals (77 jet) on 13 fixed-wing airlines from 31 airports,<ref>UA had 25 flights from DEN, DSM, MLI, LGA, OMA, PIT, and DCA; AA had 13 from DTW, EWR, ROC and STL; NW had 10 from MSP and CLE.</ref> but the August 1974 shows 14 arrivals (all jet) on four airlines, and in 1976\u201379 Midway had only the two or three Delta DC-9s from St Louis. [[Midway Airlines (1976\u20131991)|Midway Airlines]] arrived on October 31, 1979 with DC-9 nonstops to Kansas City, Detroit and Cleveland Lakefront; they expanded greatly in the 1980s. Their September 1989 timetable shows 117 weekday departures to 29 cities, plus 108 departures on their commuter affiliates to 22 more cities. Midway quit flying in 1991.\n\nIn 1982, the city of Chicago purchased Midway Airport from the Chicago Board of Education for $16&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.flychicago.com/events/KidsPage2006/MidwayHistory.shtm \n |title=History of Midway International Airport \n |publisher=Fly Chicago \n |date=April 28, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070606142133/http://www.flychicago.com/events/KidsPage2006/MidwayHistory.shtm \n |archivedate=June 6, 2007 \n}}</ref> Three years later, [[Southwest Airlines]] began operations at Midway.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.southwest.com/about_swa/press/factsheet.html#Top%20Ten%20Airports\n| title = Southwest Airlines Fact Sheet: Top Ten Airports\n| publisher = Southwest Airlines\n| date = May 12, 2007\n| access-date = April 8, 2007\n| archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/67CSoDlS9?url=http://www.southwest.com/html/about-southwest/history/fact-sheet.html#Top%20Ten%20Airports\n| archive-date = April 26, 2012\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> Midway was a focus city for [[Vanguard Airlines]] from 1997 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/2775.html|title=Midway Airlines|publisher=Encyclopedia of Chicago|date=April 27, 2007|access-date=April 28, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070423150615/http://encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/2775.html|archive-date=April 23, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Chicago Transit Authority]] displaced the Carlton Midway Inn to open a new [[Midway station (CTA)|CTA terminal]] at the airport on October 31, 1993, for the new [[Chicago \"L\"|Chicago 'L']] [[Orange Line (CTA)|Orange Line]] that connected Midway to the Loop.<ref name=\"visitorsguide\" /> Midway Airport is the end of the line, which crosses the southwest part of the city before ending at the Loop. The Orange Line does not run 24 hours a day (unlike the Blue Line, which has 24-hour service to {{cta|O'Hare}}), but does operate from about 4:00&nbsp;am to 1:00&nbsp;am, at an average of 8-minute intervals. (However, during overnight periods, the <code>N62 Archer</code> bus is provided as an alternative.) The trip from Midway to the Loop takes 25 minutes.\n\n===Years of ATA (1994\u20132008)===\nIn 1996, after failing to get his [[Proposed Chicago south suburban airport|Lake Calumet Airport]] and having received harsh criticism for the idea of turning the airport into an industrial park, Chicago [[Richard M. Daley|Mayor Richard M. Daley]] announced the Midway Airport Terminal Development Program, which was launched the following year. At the time, it was the largest public works project in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetracon.com/MidwayHistory.htm |title=Early History/Post O'hare history |publisher=The Tracon |date=April 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010043335/http://www.thetracon.com/MidwayHistory.htm |archivedate=October 10, 2013 }}</ref> The Midway Airport parking garage opened in 1999, bringing covered parking to the airport for the first time. The garage is connected to the Midway terminal building for convenient access to ticket counters and baggage claim areas.<ref name=\"visitorsguide\" />\n\nContinuing with the expansion project, a pedestrian bridge over Cicero Avenue was built in 2000, connecting the new terminal to the new concourses.<ref name=\"history\" /> In 2001 the new {{convert|900000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Midway Airport terminal building opened, with larger ticket counters, spacious baggage claim areas, traveler information, and a short walking distance to gates.<ref name=\"visitorsguide\" /> A {{convert|50000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} food court opened with Chicago-style food and retail options.\n\nThe expansion project culminated with a short lived period of great airline diversity at Midway as [[Vanguard Airlines]], [[National Airlines (1934\u20131980)|National Airlines]] and [[AirTran Airways]] all expanded their services to the airport.\n\n[[ATA Airlines]] (ATA) took over [[Chicago Express Airlines]], also known as ATA Connection, whose primary hub was at Midway.\nChicago Express served as a regional airline connecting to airports around the great lakes regions.\n\nFollowing the [[September 11 attacks]], which resulted in a drop in passenger service, along with other problems for the airline industry, both Vanguard and National ceased operations at Midway and became defunct in 2002, with MetroJet being dissolved and refolded into US Airways' main line in late 2001.\n\nIn 2002 Midway welcomed the return of international service after a 40-year absence with the opening of the new Federal Inspection Service facility in Concourse A.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airport-technology.com/projects/midway/|title=New Midway Terminal|publisher=Airport-Technology.com|date=April 6, 2007|access-date=April 6, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208192554/http://www.airport-technology.com/projects/midway/|archive-date=December 8, 2006|url-status=live}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2004, Mayor Daley and airline officials celebrated the completion of the Terminal Development Program.<ref name=\"history\" /> The project, designed by [[HNTB]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hntb.com/our-work/projects/chicago-midway-airport-%E2%80%93-chicago-illinois|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701113937/http://www.hntb.com/our-work/projects/chicago-midway-airport-%E2%80%93-chicago-illinois|url-status=dead|title=HNTB \u2013 Chicago Midway Airport|archivedate=July 1, 2012}}</ref> resulted in the addition of 14 gates (from 29 to 43).<ref name=\"history\" /> A new 6,300-space economy parking garage, including a new bridge and roadway for buses shuttling passengers to and from the terminal, opened in December 2005.<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nSimultaneous to Midway's expansion, [[ATA Airlines]] began rapid expansion at Midway in the early 2000s (decade), and was the airport's dominant carrier prior to 2004, using 14 of the 17 gates in Concourse A.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://ata.com/about_ata/company_information/facts.html | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080328103513/http://www.ata.com/about_ata/company_information/facts.html | archivedate =March 28, 2008| title = ATA Facts| publisher=ATA Airlines | date = December 1, 2007}}</ref> However, after the airline declared bankruptcy in October 2004, scheduled service from Midway significantly decreased.\n\nFor over 16 years, Midway had been the main [[airline hub|hub]] for [[Indianapolis]]-based ATA, but the airline shut down on June 7, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/flights/item.aspx?ak=40086752.blog&type=blog|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120629095440/http://www.usatoday.com/travel/flights/item.aspx?ak=40086752.blog&type=blog|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-06-29|title=ATA to end service to DCA, LGA|work=USA Today | first=Ben|last=Mutzabaugh}}</ref><ref name=\"ATA Press Release\" /> Earlier, the airline filed for bankruptcy in April 2008; on April 3, 2008, ATA Airlines discontinued all operations.<ref name=\"ATA Press Release\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=109&STORY=/www/story/03-06-2008/0004769303&EDATE= |title=ATA Airlines to Discontinue Scheduled Service at Chicago's Midway Airport |publisher=PR Newswire |work=ATA Airlines |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314142651/http://www2.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=109&STORY=%2Fwww%2Fstory%2F03-06-2008%2F0004769303&EDATE= |archivedate=March 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, [[Porter Airlines]], which flies between Midway and [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport]], was the only international route served from Chicago\u2013Midway after [[ATA Airlines]], which had flights to [[Mexico]], ceased operations in April that year. On December 13, 2010, a second carrier, [[Volaris]], began flights between [[Guadalajara]] and Midway.\n\nStarting in early 2009, a construction project added a new walkway and food court to Concourse A. The project also connected gates A4A and A4B to the main A concourse. Expansions were completed in the spring of 2010.\n\n===Privatization attempts===\nChicago has considered privatizing the airport, but the deals fell through in 2009 and 2013.\n\nOn April 20, 2009 a $2.5&nbsp;billion deal to [[privatize]] the airport via a 99-year lease fell through when the consortium could not put together financing. The city would have kept $125&nbsp;million in the down payment. The consortium operating under the name of Midway Investment and Development Company LLC consisted of [[Vancouver Airport Services]], [[Citigroup|Citi]] Infrastructure Investors, and Boston's [[John Hancock Insurance|John Hancock Life Insurance]]. It was awarded the contract in October 2008 by the City Council, which voted 49\u20130 to approve it. The consortium would have operated the airport and collected airport parking, concession, and passenger facility charges. However, Chicago would have continued to provide fire and police services. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chicagotribune.newspapers.com/|title=Chicago Tribune - Historical Newspapers|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=July 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419220724/http://archives.chicagotribune.com/2009/mar/12/business/chi-biz-sears-tower-name-change-willis-march12|archive-date=April 19, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010 a new slogan emerged calling the airport ''The busiest square mile in the world.\n\nIn September 2013, Mayor [[Rahm Emanuel]] terminated new negotiations to privatize the airport, noting that the process was no longer competitive after one of the two finalists had backed out. The one remaining was Great Lakes Airport Alliance \u2013 a partnership of [[Macquarie Group|Macquarie Infrastructure and Real Assets]] and [[Ferrovial]]. Macquarie was one of the investors in the Chicago Skyway. The group that had backed out was a group that included the Australia-based Industry Funds Management and [[Manchester Airports Group]]. The Great Lakes proposal had been valued at $2 billion and would have involved a 40-year lease.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324577304579057483001629874 Chicago Halts Airport Lease \u2013 WSJ.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314105319/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324577304579057483001629874 |date=March 14, 2016 }}. Online.wsj.com (September 5, 2013). Retrieved on September 18, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-09-06/news/chi-emanuel-halts-midway-lease-talks-20130905_1_great-lakes-airport-alliance-midway-airport-midway-advisory-panel Emanuel halts Midway privatization bidding \u2013 Chicago Tribune] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090021/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-09-06/news/chi-emanuel-halts-midway-lease-talks-20130905_1_great-lakes-airport-alliance-midway-airport-midway-advisory-panel |date=March 4, 2016 }}. Articles.chicagotribune.com (September 6, 2013). Retrieved on September 18, 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Modernization program ===\nConstruction began in 2018 on expansions of the security checkpoint and main parking garage. The bridge spanning Cicero Ave is being widened from 50 feet to over 400 feet, allowing up to 17 security lanes and a streamlined queue.<ref name=\"mp\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.flychicago.com/sites/midwaymodernization/projects/Pages/checkpoint.aspx|title=Midway modernization|website=www.flychicago.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-09-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916060144/https://www.flychicago.com/sites/midwaymodernization/projects/Pages/checkpoint.aspx|archive-date=September 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As the current terminal opened just a few months prior to the September 11th attacks, the security area was quickly rendered too small for the new screening measures and subsequently was forced to expand inward, taking away from space in the concourses. Space that is reclaimed by moving security outward into the bridge will be redeveloped with an expansion of the central food court. The main parking garage is being extended eastward over the CTA L tracks to add 1,500 spaces and streamline the entrance way.<ref name=\"mp\"/> In addition to the redeveloped central food court, new concession options will open in phases including a food court in Concourse A utilizing previously unused space built during the 2010 rebuild of the Gate A4A/B connecting walkway.<ref name=\"mp\"/> The program is the largest capital improvements project at the airport since the 2001 terminal redevelopment and is scheduled to be completed winter 2019-2020.\n\n==Airfield==\n[[File:MDW 5.JPG|thumb|Main Corridor at Chicago\u2013Midway.]]\n[[File:MDW 6.JPG|thumb|[[Southwest Airlines]] check-in ticket counters.]]\nAll terminals and hangars were on the square periphery. By the late 1970s, the shorter north\u2013south and east\u2013west runway pairs had been closed, though some were converted to taxiways. The other four runways remain in use, all strengthened and enhanced, but about the same lengths as always. A short runway (13R/31L) for light aircraft was added in 1989.\n\nChicago Midway International Airport covers just over one square mile ({{convert|650|acres|disp=or}})<ref name=\"FAA\" /> and has five runways:<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.airnav.com/airport/KMDW| title = MDW FAA Information effective 11 February 2010| publisher = AirNav| date = February 11, 2010| access-date = April 6, 2007| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070416030027/http://www.airnav.com/airport/KMDW| archive-date = April 16, 2007| url-status = live}}</ref>\n* 13C/31C: {{convert|6522|x|150|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, air carrier runway, [[Instrument landing system|ILS]]-equipped.\n* 4R/22L: {{convert|6445|x|150|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, air carrier runway, ILS-equipped.\n* 4L/22R: {{convert|5507|x|150|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, general aviation and air taxi.\n* 13L/31R: {{convert|5141|x|150|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, general aviation and air taxi. Used as an Emergency Runway for commercial aircraft{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}.\n* 13R/31L: {{convert|3859|x|60|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, light aircraft only. Used as an Emergency Runway for commercial aircraft{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}.\n\nMidway is surrounded by buildings and other development, so the landing thresholds of the runways are [[displaced threshold|displaced]] to provide obstacle clearance. The [[Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]] and the airlines ensure safety by adhering to calculated load limits and various weather minimums. Because of the displaced landing thresholds, the runways have shorter distances available for landings than for takeoffs. 13C/31C, the longest runway, only has an available landing distance of {{convert|6059|ft|m}} in the southeast direction, and {{convert|5826|ft|m}} to the northwest. The largest aircraft normally seen at Midway is the [[Boeing 757]]. Normally, commercial planes only take off from and land on runways 4R/22L and 13C/31C. The other runways are used by smaller aircraft.\n\n==Terminals==\nMidway has 43 aircraft gates on three concourses (A, B, and C).<ref name=\"visitorsguide\" /> The three concourses and their gates are:\n\n*Concourse A \u2013 17 gates (A1\u2013A3, A4a, A4b, A5, A7\u2013A12, A14\u2013A19). Airlines assigned to this concourse are Delta, Porter, Volaris and Southwest\n*Concourse B \u2013 23 gates (B1\u2013B3, B5, B7\u2013B12, B14\u2013B26). Airlines assigned to this concourse are Southwest\n*Concourse C \u2013 3 gates (C1\u2013C3). Airlines assigned to this concourse are North Country Sky\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list | 3rdcoltitle = Refs | 3rdcolunsortable=yes\n<!--DO NOT ADD TERMINAL/CONCOURSE INFORMATION TO THIS TABLE AS IT VIOLATES [[WP:NOTTRAVEL]]-->\n<!-- -->\n| [[Allegiant Air]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Lehigh Valley International Airport|Allentown]] (begins May 14, 2020),<ref name=ALL /> [[Asheville Regional Airport|Asheville]] (begins May 21, 2020),<ref name=ALL /> [[Des Moines International Airport|Des Moines]] (begins May 21, 2020),<ref name=ALL /> [[Destin\u2013Fort Walton Beach Airport|Destin/Fort Walton Beach]] (begins June 5, 2020),<ref name=ALL>{{cite web|url=http://ir.allegiantair.com/news-releases/news-release-details/allegiant-announces-largest-service-expansion-company-history-3|title=Allegiant Announces Largest Service Expansion In Company History With 3 New Cities And 44 Nonstop Routes|publisher=Allegiant Airlines}}</ref> [[McGhee Tyson Airport|Knoxville]] (begins May 21, 2020),<ref name=ALL /> [[Savannah/Hilton Head International Airport|Savannah]] (begins May 21, 2020)<ref name=ALL /> | <ref>{{cite web|title=Allegiant Interactive Route Map|url=https://www.allegiantair.com/interactive-routemap|accessdate=14 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717045737/https://www.allegiantair.com/interactive-routemap|archive-date=July 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Delta Air Lines]] | [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta]]<br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Detroit Metropolitan Airport|Detroit]] | <ref name=\"DeltaRoutes\">{{cite web|title=FLIGHT SCHEDULES|url=https://www.delta.com/flightinfo/viewFlightSchedulesSetup.action|accessdate=7 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621123636/http://www.delta.com/flightinfo/viewFlightSchedulesSetup.action|archive-date=June 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Delta Connection]] | [[Detroit Metropolitan Airport|Detroit]], [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis/St. Paul]] | <ref name=\"DeltaRoutes\"/>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Porter Airlines]] | [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport|Toronto\u2013Billy Bishop]] | <ref name=\"PorterRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Fly porter destinations|url=https://www.flyporter.com/en-ca/book-flights/where-we-fly/route-map|accessdate=26 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227151656/https://www.flyporter.com/en-ca/book-flights/where-we-fly/route-map|archive-date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| {{nowrap|[[Southwest Airlines]]}} | [[Albany International Airport|Albany]], [[Albuquerque International Sunport|Albuquerque]], [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta]], [[Austin\u2013Bergstrom International Airport|Austin]], [[Baltimore\u2013Washington International Airport|Baltimore]], [[Birmingham\u2013Shuttlesworth International Airport|Birmingham (AL)]], [[Logan International Airport|Boston]], [[Buffalo Niagara International Airport|Buffalo]], [[Hollywood-Burbank Airport|Burbank]], [[Canc\u00fan International Airport|Canc\u00fan]], [[Charleston International Airport|Charleston (SC)]], [[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]], [[Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport|Cincinnati]], [[Cleveland Hopkins International Airport|Cleveland]], [[John Glenn Columbus International Airport|Columbus\u2013Glenn]], [[Dallas Love Field|Dallas\u2013Love]], [[Denver International Airport|Denver]], [[Detroit Metropolitan Airport|Detroit]], [[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Southwest Florida International Airport|Fort Myers]], [[Gerald R. Ford International Airport|Grand Rapids]], [[Bradley International Airport|Hartford]], [[William P. Hobby Airport|Houston\u2013Hobby]], [[Indianapolis International Airport|Indianapolis]], [[Jacksonville International Airport|Jacksonville (FL)]], [[Kansas City International Airport|Kansas City]], [[McCarran International Airport|Las Vegas]], [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], [[Louisville International Airport|Louisville]], [[Manchester\u2013Boston Regional Airport|Manchester (NH)]], [[Memphis International Airport|Memphis]], [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis/St. Paul]], [[Sangster International Airport|Montego Bay]], [[Nashville International Airport|Nashville]], [[Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport|New Orleans]], [[LaGuardia Airport|New York\u2013LaGuardia]], [[Norfolk International Airport|Norfolk]], [[Oakland International Airport|Oakland]], [[Will Rogers World Airport|Oklahoma City]], [[Eppley Airfield|Omaha]], [[Ontario International Airport|Ontario]], [[Orlando International Airport|Orlando]], [[Pensacola International Airport|Pensacola]], [[Philadelphia International Airport|Philadelphia]], [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Harbor]], [[Pittsburgh International Airport|Pittsburgh]], [[Portland International Airport|Portland (OR)]], [[T. F. Green Airport|Providence]], [[Punta Cana International Airport|Punta Cana]], [[Raleigh\u2013Durham International Airport|Raleigh/Durham]], [[Sacramento International Airport|Sacramento]], [[St. Louis Lambert International Airport|St. Louis]], [[Salt Lake City International Airport|Salt Lake City]], [[San Antonio International Airport|San Antonio]], [[San Diego International Airport|San Diego]], [[San Francisco International Airport|San&nbsp;Francisco]], [[San Jose International Airport|San Jose (CA)]], [[Los Cabos International Airport|San Jos\u00e9 del Cabo]], [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn International Airport|San Juan]], [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]], [[Tampa International Airport|Tampa]], [[Tucson International Airport|Tucson]], [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|Washington\u2013National]]<br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Northwest Florida Beaches International Airport|Panama City (FL)]], [[Portland International Jetport|Portland (ME)]], [[Reno-Tahoe International Airport|Reno/Tahoe]], [[Palm Beach International Airport|West Palm Beach]] | <ref name=\"SouthwestRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Check Flight Schedules|url=https://www.southwest.com/air/flight-schedules/index.html|accessdate=7 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202053931/https://www.southwest.com/air/flight-schedules/index.html|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| {{nowrap|[[Ultimate Air Shuttle]]}} | [[Cincinnati Municipal Lunken Airport|Cincinnati\u2013Lunken]] | <ref name=\"UltimateDestionations\">{{cite web|title=Ultimate Air Shuttle Timetable|url=http://ultimateairshuttle.com/pdf/allcities.pdf|accessdate=23 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616013624/http://ultimateairshuttle.com/pdf/allcities.pdf|archive-date=June 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Volaris]] |[[Aguascalientes International Airport|Aguascalientes]], [[Durango International Airport|Durango]], [[Guadalajara International Airport|Guadalajara]], [[Del Baj\u00edo International Airport|Le\u00f3n/Del Baj\u00edo]], [[Morelia International Airport|Morelia]], [[Zacatecas International Airport|Zacatecas]] | <ref name=\"VolarisRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Volaris Flight Schedule|url=http://cms.volaris.com/en/travel-with-volaris/flight-information/complete-timetable-of-our-flights/|accessdate=26 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227151536/http://cms.volaris.com/en/travel-with-volaris/flight-information/complete-timetable-of-our-flights/|archive-date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n}}\n\n==Statistics==\nChicago Midway Airport is the second-largest passenger airport in the state of [[Illinois]], with only O'Hare being larger.<ref name=\"Chicago Airport System\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flychicago.com/statistics/airportstatistics.shtm|title=Chicago Airport System Airport Statistics|date=December 1, 2007|publisher=Chicago Airport System|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218063025/http://www.flychicago.com/statistics/airportstatistics.shtm|archivedate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Chicago Midway International Airport was the 27th-busiest airport in the United States and 29th-busiest airport in North America in terms of passenger traffic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://airportscouncil.org/intelligence/north-american-airport-traffic-reports/http://www.aci-na.org/content/airport-traffic-reports|title=Airport Traffic Reports - Airports Council International - North America|website=www.aci-na.org|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, Midway International Airport has approximately 221 daily direct flights to 58 U.S. cities and approximately 12 daily direct flights to 11 international destinations. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flychicago.com/midway/myflight/non-stop/pages/default.aspx|title=Non-stop Service|website=www.flychicago.com|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Southwest Airlines|Southwest]] is the dominant carrier at Midway, controlling 34 of the airport's 43 gates. Currently, the airline offers around 236 daily departures to 67 nonstop destinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwest.com/about_swa/press/factsheet.html#Fleet|title=Southwest's Daily Departures from MDW|publisher=Southwest Airlines|access-date=April 8, 2007|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/67CSoDlS9?url=http://www.southwest.com/html/about-southwest/history/fact-sheet.html#Fleet|archive-date=April 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nChicago Midway ranked highest in customer satisfaction among medium-sized airports (10&nbsp;million to 30 million passengers per year) in [[J. D. Power and Associates]]' 2008 study.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.jdpower.com/corporate/news/releases/pdf/2008050.pdf | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080625030120/http://www.jdpower.com/corporate/news/releases/pdf/2008050.pdf | archivedate = June 25, 2008 | title = Customer Satisfaction with Airports Declines Sharply Amid an Industry Fraught with Flight Delays | publisher=J.D. Power and Associates | date = May 20, 2008}}</ref>\n\n\n\n===Annual traffic===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Annual passenger traffic at MDW<br />2000\u2013Present'''<ref name=\"CAS\" />\n! Year !! Passengers !! Year !! Passengers\n|-\n| 2000||15,672,688||2010||17,676,413\n|-\n| 2001||15,628,886||2011||18,883,170\n|-\n| 2002||16,959,229||2012||19,516,127\n|-\n| 2003||18,644,372||2013||20,474,552\n|-\n| 2004||19,718,236||2014||21,179,833\n|-\n| 2005||17,862,838||2015||22,221,499\n|-\n| 2006||18,868,388||2016||22,677,589\n|-\n| 2007||19,378,855||2017||22,460,236\n|-\n| 2008||17,345,635||2018||22,027,737\n|-\n| 2009||17,089,365||2019||20,844,860\n|}\n\n===Top destinations===\n[[File:MDW 13.JPG|thumb|Sculpture at Chicago\u2013Midway.]]\n[[File:MDW 10.JPG|thumb|[[SBD Dauntless]] on static display as part of the [[Battle of Midway|Midway]] memorial.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|+ '''Busiest domestic routes from MDW (February 2019 \u2013 January 2020)'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transtats.bts.gov/airports.asp?pn=1&Airport=MDW|title=Chicago, IL: Chicago Midway International (MDW)|publisher=[[Bureau of Transportation Statistics]], [[United States Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! Rank\n! City\n! Passengers\n! Carriers\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| 467,000\n| Delta, Southwest\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Denver International Airport|Denver, Colorado]]\n| 410,000\n| Southwest\n|-\n| 3\n| [[McCarran International Airport|Las Vegas, Nevada]]\n| 400,000\n| Southwest\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Orlando International Airport|Orlando, Florida]]\n| 374,000\n| Southwest\n|-\n| 5\n| [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis/St. Paul, Minnesota]]\n| 361,000\n| Delta, Southwest\n|-\n| 6\n| [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Har